If the queue is designed for only one data type at a time, then you are doing things generically at the method level, which should be done at the class level.  In other words, instead of :

    var queue = SuperQ.SuperQ.GetQueue("MyQueue");
    queue.StartReceiving&lt;string&gt;(MessageReceived);
    queue.PushMessage&lt;string&gt;(new QueueMessage&lt;string&gt;("P was pressed in message form"));
    var message = queue.GetMessage&lt;string&gt;();

It should be:

    var queue = SuperQ.SuperQ.GetQueue&lt;string&gt;("MyQueue");
    queue.StartReceiving(MessageReceived);
    queue.PushMessage(new QueueMessage&lt;string&gt;("P was pressed in message form"));
    var message = queue.GetMessage();

Further, you should probably have two PushMessage method; one, defined as it is current, and one which automatically wraps the object:

    public  void PushMessage(T message)
    {
           PushMessage(new QueueMessage&lt;T&gt;(message));
    }

That would allow you to write:

    queue.PushMessage("P was pressed in message form");

